## Writing a Method

```dart
class Player {
  String name;
  int health;
  Player(this.name, this.health);

  // This is a Method!
  void takeDamage() {
    health -= 10;
    print('$name took damage! Health is now $health.');
  }
}
```
Because `takeDamage()` lives inside `Player`, it instantly has access to `name` and `health`!

## The Dot Operator Returns

Just like we use the dot `.` to access properties, we use it to trigger Methods on the object.

```dart
void main() {
  Player p1 = Player('Mario', 100);

  // Trigger the action!
  p1.takeDamage(); 
  p1.takeDamage(); 
}
```
Every time you call it, `p1`'s health drops by 10!

